<section xml:id="sec_waves_string" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Waves on a String</title>
  
  
<p>
A mechanical wave is an organized disturbance which travels outward from the source of the wave through a medium at the wave speed <m> \nu </m>. Let's consider a stretched string of length <m> L </m>, mass <m> m </m>, with tension <m> T_s </m>, and <alert> linear density </alert> <m> \mu_s</m> where 

<me> \mu_s = \frac{m}{L}</me>

is the mass-to-length ratio of the string. The wave speed <m> \nu </m>

<me> \nu_{string} = \sqrt{\frac{T_s}{\mu_s}} </me>

depends on the tension which serves as a restoring force for the medium and the linear density of the string. 
</p>
